<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-438-519  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 438 519.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Sept 17 1990 v24 n38 p25(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>One man's 'natural' is another's 'what is this?' (computer inputdevices) (Viewpoint) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Newquist, Harvey P. III.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The 'naturalness' of a natural language user interface depends onthe skills and preferences of the user.andP;  For those with illegiblehandwriting, input devices that read handwriting cannot interpretm 'chicken scratches.' Further, for long-time keyboard users,handwritten input is slow and cumbersome.andP;  Voice recognitionsystems, while envisioned as the ultimate in natural userinterfaces, may be more difficult to use than some developersrealize.andP;  Using a dictaphone, especially to compose lengthydocuments, is difficult for novices who may write more accuratelyand efficiently at a keyboard.andP;  Experience with various operatingsystems and graphical user interfaces also affects how natural anew input method may feel to a particular user.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     I-O DevicesUser InterfaceNatural Language Interfaces.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>